description:
The Finish Line Bike Fest ride will take place April 13, 2013 at Finish Line bike shop. There will be a 50 mile, 20 mile and a 10 mile family ride. At the event Jeff Lenoskey, world famous bicycle stunt rider, will be performing. Giant Bicycle Co. will also be bringing their demo trucks with limited amounts of men\'s and women\'s bicycles to demo on the ride routes. Also at the event will be vendors from the bicycle industry as well as local.
All the proceeds from this event will be going to benefit Bikes for Bakersfield, a local charity that distributes bicycles to under privilege children in the Bakersfield area during the Christmas Holiday. Last year over 400 bicycles were delivered to these deserving children.

The entry cost for the 10 mi family ride will be $50 preregistration and $60 ride day registration, which includes entry for four, (2) T-shirts and (4) BBQ lunches. We will have event jerseys which can be purchased separate for $80
directions: Finish Line Bike shop is located at 8850 Stockdale Hwy, Bakersfield, CA. We are at the corner of Stockdale Hwy and Don Hart Dr East directly accross from California State University Bakersfield.

Echelon Gran Fondo - Sonoma
description:
Its home to Wine Spectators Wine of the Year, and to more than 500 wineries. It boasts two of only 10 Michelin three-star restaurants in the United States. Oh yeah it also produces Beer Advocates best beer in the world. If you havent enjoyed yourself enough  or perhaps too much  perhaps youll spend a day in one of 70 spas or 50 golf courses. Or just float down the Russian River

And of course, this is the epicenter of American cycling. Professional riders, bike builders and weekend warriors alike know that this the epitome of cycling grandeur. Rolling vineyard-covered hills. Dense canopy-sheltered roadways. Immaculate coastlines. Redwoods. No cars in sight.
course:
Our course starts and finishes in the heart of Sonoma, on the historic town square that showcases the towns Mexican colonial past and was once the capital of the California Republic.

From the start riders will exit town to the East, and within just a couple miles will be rolling into Napa County. Mini riders will enjoy a flat course out and back. The Gran and Medio riders will get a warm-up incline at mile 15, with the first real challenge at mile 22, where youll gain 1100 feet in 7 miles, drop 700 feet fast, then climb 1000 feet again.

Gran riders face another 800 feet just past the Glen Ellin rest stop, then its a relatively easy pedal back to celebr-er, civilization.
registration: http://www.eventbrite.com/event/3691744106?ref=ebtn
notes: Upon return to Sonoma, the finest offerings await. More than a dozen local restaurants provide riders with replenishment. Joining them are the eager representatives of the Sonoma Vintners & Growers Alliance, and a handful of the countys famous brewers. See our Party page for developing details.

title: Hotter 'N Hell Hillclimb at Mt. Baldy
Fast Freddie Gran Fondo
description:
Despite sharing part of our course with the Amgen Tour of California...despite the presence of decorated pro riders...despite the internal will to challenge oneself -- (aww stop already!) -- We see a Gran Fondo as a casual ride thats all about camaraderie, community, charity, and a huge party at the end.

Here that party centers on the 98-year-old historical landmark that is The Claremont Hotel Club and Spa. This amazing, 22-acre expanse of a property that has been a temporary home to celebrities and statesmen alike. Brangelina and the kids stayed here while Brad Pitt was filming Moneyball...for those of you scoring at home. The Claremont hosts our entire weekend, from Friday night packet pick-up and reception to our post-race festival to your Sunday recovery. There could be no better host to spend a few room-nights with...

The weekend starts on Friday with our rider reception and packet pickup. Meet your fellow riders and hosting pros in The Horizon Room, which offers just that: a panoramic view of the San Francisco Bay, skyline and sunset over the Golden Gate Bridge.

Your ride begins at 8 AM on the lower lot of the resort grounds, and returns you there for the post-race festival featuring the requisite sponsor schmoozing and an epicurean experience of local artisan fare, wineries and breweries.

Riders staying with us into the night may join us for live music and perfect-weather patio-ing at the Claremonts Paragon Restaurant and Bar. Or perhaps youll opt for the finer dining of Meritage.

No, were not done. Youll also need to stop by the spa, which will have cyclist-specific packages awaiting you. Named among the 10 best spas of its kind in the country by Vogue, Elle, and Shape magazines, its 22,000 square feet offer rejuvenation haven.

You will want to spend the weekend here. Book your stay soon.
course:
This is a wilderness oasis -- 112,000 acres -- amidst one of the most densely populated areas in the country. Looming in the center of it all is the monster: Mount Diablo. Diablo means devil, but dont be afraid. Its only a 1500 foot climb over seven miles that maxes out at a 7% grade.

Dont be surprised if you find yourself at mile 45 hugging a park ranger at the station that finally grants you the mercy of a decent. Short course riders will get off a little easier, but still be challenged before coasting into the luxury of a 22 acre, century-old Oakland City Historical Landmark of a hotel. Even if youre local, you may want to treat yourself to a room night here.
registration: http://ffgranfondo-es2005.eventbrite.com/
directions: http://www.claremontresort.com/hotel_directions.shtml

Winter Training Program powered by CCSD
description:
The Winter Training Program powered by CCSD is a three-month training program starting at the end of October and finishing at the end of January. Athletes will receive daily periodized workouts based on power or heart rate parameters via TrainingPeaks. In addition, athletes will participate in a weekly Sunday progressive structured training ride.

This program is coached by Level 2 and Level 1 USAC coaches, plus a former professional cyclist. This program is limited to 12 athletes. By attending the complete program, athletes receive 4 qualifying race days for a category 5 to 4 upgrade, or 3 upgrade points for a category 4 to 3 upgrade.

description: This is a non-competitive training ride for USCF licensed racers riding counter-clockwise around the "Mini Hills" loop in the Claremont/Laverne/San Dimas/Covina area. The event is intended for experienced riders and the pace will be moderate to fast with several moderate but short climbs. The ride will begin and end at the Coffee Bean on Indian Hill in Claremont. The course route may be changed at the start by the organizer due to weather, traffic or event turn out.
course: An approximately 30 mile loop through neighboring cities. Traffic should be light to moderate on secondary and primary roads with some sections requiring single file riding.
registration: Registration will be located in the open public area adjacent to the Coffee Bean, known as Smokers Alley" on Indian Hill Ave. in downtown Claremont. Registration will be open from 6:45am to 7:00am.
notes: All USCF rules apply. Helmets are mandatory at all times while on your bike. Shirts must cover shoulders. No fixed gears. No tandems. Route is open to traffic and all traffic laws apply. Riders are responsible for their own safety with traffic and other bikes.
directions: From the East or West, exit at Towne Ave. off the 210 Fwy. Go South to Foothill Blvd. and turn left. Continue East until Indian Hill Ave and turn right. The ride will begin at the Coffee Bean on the West side of the road between W. Bonita Ave. and W. 2nd St.
